*poetarum quam oratorum similior oratio: poetarum quam ora- torum orationum . . . oratio. An example of the so-called ‘ compa- ratio compendiaria,' by which the property belonging to the person or thing is directly compared with the person or with the thing itself. This brachylogy is often employed to avoid the awkward repetition

pronoun. In Tacitus the construction is rare, e. g. G. 46 quae omnia diversa Sarmatis (= moribus Sarmatarum) sunt. Ag. 24 solum caelumque et ingenia cultusque hominum haud multum a Britannia differt.
